[build] #48 8.221 This renders your charts locally (without tiller) and
[build] #48 8.221 validates the rendered output with the tests defined in
[build] #48 8.221 test suite files. Simplest test suite file looks like
[build] #48 8.221 below:
[build] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 ---
[build] #48 8.221 # CHART_PATH/tests/deployment_test.yaml
[build] #48 8.221 suite: test my deployment
[build] #48 8.221 templates:
[build] #48 8.221   - deployment.yaml
[build] #48 8.221 tests:
[build] #48 8.221   - it: should be a Deployment
[build] #48 8.221     asserts:
[build] #48 8.221       - isKind:
[build] #48 8.221           of: Deployment
[build] #48 8.221 ---
[build] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 Put the test files in "tests" directory under your chart
[build] #48 8.221 with suffix "_test.yaml", and run:
[build] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 $ helm unittest my-chart
[build] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 Or specify the suite files glob path pattern:
[build] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 $ helm unittest -f 'my-tests/*.yaml' my-chart
[build] [2026-05-10T22:36:43.756Z] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 Check https://github.com/helm-unittest/helm-unittest for more
[build] #48 8.221 details about how to write tests.
[build] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 Usage:
[build] #48 8.221   unittest [flags] CHART [...]
[build] #48 8.221 
[build] #48 8.221 Flags:
[build] #48 8.221       --chart-tests-path string   chart-tests-path the folder location relative to the chart where a helm chart to render test suites is located
[build] #48 8.221       --color                     enforce printing colored output even stdout is not a tty. Set to false to disable color
[build] #48 8.221   -d, --debugPlugin               enable verbose output
[build] #48 8.221   -q, --failfast                  actually directly quit testing, when a test is failed
[build] #48 8.221   -f, --file stringArray          glob paths of test files location, default to tests/*_test.yaml
[build] #48 8.221   -h, --help                      help for unittest
[build] #48 8.221   -o, --output-file string        output-file the file where testresults are written in JUnit format, defaults no output is written to file
